<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Scope (JRR 0019)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">About Scope</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">1.1 Scope exists to make this country a better place for disabled people and their families. We do this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> by running a range of services, raising awareness of the issues that disabled people face and influencing change across society.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We provide support, advice and information for more than a quarter of a million disabled people and their family members every</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">1.2 Scope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> submission focuses on the questions relating to the proposed changes to the costs of judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ability of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> disabled people to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">local authorities around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">social care decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Scope recognises that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">judicial review is, and should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> continue to be a remedy of last resort. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he pursuit of a judicial review case has meant that disabled people have been able to challenge decisions by public bodies which adversely affect their lives across a range of areas –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> such as seeking redress against unlawful reduction in the support they get to live an independent life or against treatment that may result in arbitrary deprivation of liberty. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.2 In some circumstances, notably in the absence of a statutory right of ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">peal, judicial review may be the only route through which a range of crucial statutory duties that local authorities have – such as, for instance, the duty to assess a disabled person who may be in need of community care services – are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">safeguarded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> recent example of this was the use of judicial review by five disabled people to challenge the Government’s decision to close the Independent Living Fund (ILF). The ILF provides financial support to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">19,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">000 disabled people which enables</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> them to live </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ndependently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in the community rather than move into residential care. In November of this year, the court of appeal ruled in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">favour of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the five ILF cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">aimant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s and stated that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">there was insufficient evidence that the 'very grave impact' on some of those affe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">cted by the closure of the ILF was properly brought to the Minister's attention, despite officials having been clearly informed of the possible impacts not only by service users but also by local authorities</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As a result of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the ruling, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) confirmed that it had accepted the court’s decision and would not seek leave to appeal, and stated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">“ministers will be invited to make a new decision on the future of the Independent Livin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">g Fund based on further a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">dvice…to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">make sure the equality duty is ade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">quately adhered to”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.5 Given the vital importance of judicial review in preserving basic fundamental rights,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> as demonstrated in the above case,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Scope would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">strongly oppose any proposals whose effect would be to make it more difficult for disabled people to bring such claims. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.6 The importance of judicial review should also be viewed in the context of the Governments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">proposed reforms to social care. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he Gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ernment have committed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">radically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">reforming the social care system, setting out the first legislative framework for adult social care in England through the Care Bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> which is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">passing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Parliament. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">At a time of considerable change in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">social care system,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">it is likely that j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">udicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">will be a crucial last resort for working age disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in ensuring the new care system works as the Government intends. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">2.7 With regards the Government’s proposal to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> an alternative, non-judicial mechanism for resolving disputes about whether public bodies have complied with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Public Sector Equality D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">uty, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Scope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> endorse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> views of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Equality and Diversity Forum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> (of which we are a member)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">n this issue which are s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">et out in a separate submission to this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">inq</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">uiry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Costs</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">is proposing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">rebalancing of financial incentives so that providers are only paid for work carried out on judicial review cases where permission is granted, or exceptionally in the Legal Aid Agency’s discretion. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.2 This would mean that if a lawyer has started a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">judicial review claim, but it settles or is withdrawn before of a judge grants permission to carry on to a hearing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, they should not be paid for the work they’ve done. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ccording to the Ministry of Justice’s own impact assessment on the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ir proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in 2012 over 40% of all applications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">are withdrawn before a permission decision is made</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.3 Lawyers will therefore be deterred from bringing judicial review claims generally, even those with good prospects for success. Disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> will find it impossible to get legal advice and find someone to represent them in judicial review challenges and will therefore be left with no recourse to challenge unlawful decisions, leaving public authorities shielded away from legitimate challenges.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.4 It is also important to note that even unsuccessful review applications can serve important functions: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">“A good example is the recent Supreme Court decision in R (KM) v Cambridgeshire City Council. While the claimant failed in his challenge to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Council’s decision, the case provided the Supreme Court with the opportunity to set out detailed guidance for local authorities, building on earlier case law, in respect of the requirements of section 2(1) of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">970, which is a provision of singular importance in the field of community care.” </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.5 Furthermore, p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">roposals contained in the draft Care Bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> will mean that judicial review will be an even more crucial mechanism for disabled people to ensure they receive the support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">they need to live independently, as enshrined in Article 19 of the UNCRPD.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he explanatory notes accompanying the Care Bill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">state that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">general duty of a local authority, in exercising a function in the case of an individual, is to promote that individual’s well-being.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">here a local authority fail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to have regard to this principle, they may be challenged through judicial rev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">iew.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.7 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the Government’s proposals to reform judicial review would essentially insulate public authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">from any legitimate challenges from disabled people who feel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">local authorities are not adequately promoting their “well-being” through the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> social care system. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.8 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">of course </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">vital that the regulations accompanying the Care Bill around who is eligible for social care support are as clear and consistent as possible. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As with any regulations, the eligibility criteria will be open to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">interpretation and therefore it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> will be down to case law - not the Care Bill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">- to clarify the meaning of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">criteria. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.9 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">With regards the Government’s draft eligibility criteria, there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">uncertainty about what the regulations act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ually </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">represent. In the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">’s consultation document regarding the regulations</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">states </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">are the equivalent of ‘substantial’ under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> FACS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, whereas many local authorities believe the regulations are closer to ‘mode</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">rate’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> FACS</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">3.10 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Establishing new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> regulations will therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">likely result in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a significant number of legal challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> from disabled people who need support to live independently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">but are deemed ineligible for care. If the proposed changes to legal aid f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">or judicial review cases go ahead, the burden of such legal uncertainty would largely be borne by disabled people who would find themselves being faced with even greater barriers in bringing such challenges.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Scope therefore calls on the Government not to proceed with any reforms to judicial review which would reduce the ability of disabled people to bring about such legal challenges against decisions by public bodies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/news/2013/november/commission-welcomes-court-of-appeal-decision-overturning-the-abolition-of-the-independent-living-fun/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">https://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;frm=1&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;ved=0CC0QFjAA&amp;url</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">=https%3A%2F%2Fconsult.justice.gov.uk%2Fdigital-communications%2Fjudicial-review%2Fsupporting_documents%2FJudicialreviewproposalsforfurtherreform.pdf&amp;ei=5WWTUuf3JOmI7AamjoGoDA&amp;usg=AFQjCNGHFENGggOPKL1HpyDN2iS3xW57jA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href=